<H1 ALIGN=CENTER>
Native American Legends: Man With No Head
</H1>


<font size=4>
<b>Name:</B> Man With No Head<BR>
<b>Tribal affiliation:</B> <a href="http://www.native-languages.org/hidatsa.htm">Hidatsa</a><BR>
<b>Alternate spellings:</B> Man-With-No-Head<BR>
<b>Type:</B> <a href="http://www.native-languages.org/monsters.htm">Monster</a><BR>
<b>Related figures in other tribes:</B> <a href="http://www.native-languages.org/two-face.htm">Doubleface</a> (Sioux)
<a href="http://www.native-languages.org/morelegends/headless-man.htm">Headless-Man</a> (Wichita), 
<a href="http://www.native-languages.org/morelegends/red-woman.htm">Red Woman</a> (Crow)<BR>
<BR>
</font>

In Hidatsa folklore, Man-With-No-Head was a headless monster with a gaping mouth in its shoulder. 

<H2><U>
Man-With-No-Head Stories</a>
</u></H2>

<IMG SRC="dot5.gif"  ALT="*"><B><A HREF="
http://faculty.humanities.uci.edu/tcthorne/Socec15/lodgeboyandspringboy.htm
">Lodge-Boy and Spring-Boy</a>:</B> <br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
Hidatsa myth in which Headless Man murders a pregnant woman.
<BR>

